  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding customer financial activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Implementing risk-based compliance programs\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring\n\n4. Employee Training\n- Regular AML compliance training\n- Educating staff about detection methods\n- Understanding legal reporting requirements\n\n5. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) regulations\n- Adhering to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Complying with local and international AML laws\n\n6. Internal Controls\n- Establishing clear compliance procedures\n- Creating audit trails\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant financial penalties, legal action, and potential loss of operating licenses.\n\nSpecific requirements can vary by jurisdiction and type of financial institution.",
